                                <p> By Sayed Salahuddin</p>
                                <p> KABUL, Sep 23 (Reuters) - The governor in one of  Afghanistan's main drug producing provinces said on Monday he  was prepared to stamp out opium poppy growing but money was  needed to compensate farmers.</p>
                                <p> Poppy production has surged in Afghanistan since the fall  of the Taliban last year and Afghan opium is used to make most  of the heroin sold on European streets. The next Afghan growing  season starts in two months.</p>
                                <p> "When the government orders a total ban, we want to  implement it," the governor of Nangarhar province, Haji Deen  Mohammad, told a news conference in Kabul after meeting  President Hamid Karzai.</p>
                                <p> "But we need aid and job creation projects to keep the  farmers satisfied, to stop it peacefully rather than using  force."</p>
                                <p> Karzai offered money to farmers earlier this year to  destroy poppies but the initiative had only limited success.</p>
                                <p> Many farmers were angry about the level of compensation  offered under the British-backed scheme and others complained  they destroyed their poppies but were not paid.</p>
                                <p> Diplomats and analysts say a massive aid effort is required  in rural Afghanistan to persuade farmers to abandon the  lucrative poppy trade, with road building a key ingredient to  improve access to markets for other crops.</p>
                                <p> But they say there is no sign of the money needed from the  West to embark on such a campaign.</p>
                                <p> Interior Minister Taj Mohammad Wardak said last week the  government would destroy poppy crops using chemicals sprayed  from helicopters supplied by Western governments.</p>
                                <p> BROTHER'S MURDER UNRESOLVED</p>
                                <p> Nangarhar's governor also said he was unhappy with the  government's efforts to track down the killers of his brother,  vice president Haji Abdul Qadir, who was shot in Kabul in broad  daylight in July.</p>
                                <p> Karzai's government, which blames the assassination on  members of the former Taliban regime and their al Qaeda allies,  seems to have made no progress in finding those responsible.</p>
                                <p> "I do not know who did it -- al Qaeda, Taliban or enemies  here (in Kabul)," Deen Mohammad said.</p>
                                <p> "The truth is that so far have not seen anything active on  the part of the government to assure us that the murderers will  be found," he said.</p>
                                <p> "We want this to be done. If this is not done other  ministers and personalities will be killed too."  </p>
